                    <p class="mb-0" align="left"><br><br><br>Oyster hatcheries are facilities that focus on producing oysters that farmers can grow
                        on their offshore leases. Hatcheries start by spawning broodstock (adult) oysters to create oyster larvae. These
                        larvae remain in a free-swimming, planktonic stage of development for about 2 weeks. At 2 weeks of age, oyster
                        larvae permanently attach (called settling) to a hard substrate, usually a shell or rock, provided by the hatchery.
                        When oyster larvae settle, they are called spat. Hatcheries, which usually contain nurseries as well, raise the
                        spat for several months until they are 8 to 10 mm in size. At this point, spat are called seed and are large
                        enough to be sold to a farmer and "planted" at a farm site off the coast.
