                    <p class="mb-0">
                        The process of spawning oysters and raising the larvae into seed takes months and is often unpredictable. The AGGRC is dedicated to
                        conducting research that improves oyster hatchery operations. The AGGRC has pioneered techniques to effectively and consistently
                        cryopreserve oyster sperm. Cryopreservation (or freezing) of oyster sperm can indefinitely preserve genetic material. When needed,
                        the genetic material can then be easily distributed to oyster hatcheries for spawning, decreasing the need to keep large quantities
                        of broodstock on hand and allowing those resources to be redirected elsewhere (Paniagua-Chavez & Tiersch 2001). Additionally,
                        the genetic material of many different oyster lines can be stored and accessible to hatcheries. A hatchery can then create
                        breeding programs with these oyster lines that enhance the fitness of their future oyster stock. The AGGRC has also developed
                        nonlethal methods of collecting sperm for cryopreservation, so that valuable individuals do not need to be sacrificed
                        (Yang et al. 2013). In future work, the AGGRC plans to expand their commercial scale genetic repository operations.
                        This work will streamline the process and grant hatchery owners increased access valuable genetic material.
